WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.360
So, in order to give some context of where Spark fits when you're doing data analysis

00:00:14.360 --> 00:00:18.240
in R, it makes sense to ask this question, right?

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:21.120
Like, if you have slow code, what do you do?

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:24.160
And you know, like, it could be slow code because you're dealing with a lot of data.

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:27.440
It could also be slow for other reasons, right?

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:32.080
So the answer is definitely not Spark, at least not as an entry point.

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:35.000
You know, one of the techniques that you can use is just sample data, right?

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.520
Like, if you have a lot of data, you can reduce the amount of data that you have.

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:42.360
And you know, as long as you do it properly, and you know, you can use techniques like

00:00:42.360 --> 00:00:46.840
statistical sampling, or why not, reduce the amount of data that you have, and that definitely

00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:49.160
is progress in the right direction.

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:53.360
Another technique that you can use when you have slow code is, in the same way that Joe

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:57.520
Chen was presenting in the keynote this morning, you can use ProfViz, right?

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:00.919
So if something is slow, you can look at why is it slow.

00:01:00.919 --> 00:01:03.200
It might be the case that it's your code or it's a package.

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:08.000
You might have to use the package in a different way, or you might have to change to use a

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:09.720
different package, right?

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:16.040
But definitely, ProfViz is a great tool, and you should use it when you hit this problem.

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:18.199
And the next one is scaling up, right?

00:01:18.199 --> 00:01:24.959
So the next solution is you get bigger machines, which Joe presented and also Darby on our

00:01:24.959 --> 00:01:26.320
previous session mentioned.

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:31.720
One great way of scaling up is by saying, hey, if I have a bigger machine somewhere,

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:37.239
now we can use RStudio Pro job launcher to run that particular instance on a machine

00:01:37.239 --> 00:01:39.879
with more resources.

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:44.440
For me personally, I worked last year on a package called CloudML, and it was intended

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:50.360
to take your deep learning model, package it up, and send it to Google Cloud, train

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:52.120
it, and then get the results.

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:55.080
What I've seen on the GitHub issues is that a lot of people are actually using this not

00:01:55.080 --> 00:01:58.639
for deep learning, but just in general for modeling, which is totally fine.

00:01:58.639 --> 00:02:02.080
You don't need to use it for deep learning if you don't want to.

00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:05.080
And in general, there's multiple ways of scaling up.

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:10.520
This talk is about scaling out, which means if you're scaling up and you've hit a ceiling

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:15.440
on the compute power that you have access to, or if you simply have a lot of machine

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:19.240
spare to use, what can you do to take advantage of all those machines?

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:20.919
And that's where Spark fits in.

00:02:20.919 --> 00:02:25.520
Now, this slide is not fully comprehensive.

00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:29.699
There's many other ways of scaling up and scaling out, but at least that's the context

00:02:29.699 --> 00:02:33.800
of how you would usually scale out.

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:38.039
And for those of you that prefer diagrams, this is how it looks like, right?

00:02:38.039 --> 00:02:43.479
You can scale up or scale vertically, or you can scale out or horizontally, basically

00:02:43.479 --> 00:02:45.119
by adding machines.

00:02:45.119 --> 00:02:49.880
It does mean that you need to install Spark on each machine on this cluster, but once

00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:53.520
you have Spark running on each machine, you can basically run, in this case, a linear

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:58.639
regression across all the machines without having to manually run a subset of the data

00:02:58.639 --> 00:03:00.960
and then figure out how to aggregate it.

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:03.279
So how do you use R with Spark?

00:03:03.279 --> 00:03:06.720
Well, first of all, Sparkly R is an R package.

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:08.199
You need to install it from CRAN.

00:03:08.199 --> 00:03:13.160
And the second step is you need to install Spark on that particular machine.

00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:16.440
You install it just by running Spark install, pretty straightforward.

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:21.279
And then you connect by saying spark connect master equals local.

00:03:21.279 --> 00:03:25.759
With Sparkly R, you can very easily work locally by specifying the parameter master equals

00:03:25.759 --> 00:03:31.320
local, but you can also run on a variety of cluster providers like Databricks, IBM, Microsoft,

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:35.399
and Google, or on-premise like Cloudera and MapR, et cetera.

00:03:35.399 --> 00:03:38.160
So definitely, it's the same interface.

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:39.960
You work with it locally pretty easily.

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:44.320
And then you can change this parameter and connect to a proper cluster when needed.

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:47.720
One of the design philosophies that we follow in Sparkly R was to be as friendly to the

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:49.119
R community as possible.

00:03:49.119 --> 00:03:50.600
So we try not to reinvent the wheel.

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:56.119
So if you already know how to use the plier, you can use the plier with Sparkly R.

00:03:56.119 --> 00:04:02.779
If you want to use SQL with the DBI package, you can also as well just run a DB get query

00:04:02.779 --> 00:04:07.460
and get data out of Spark in parallel with the ease of use of R.

00:04:07.460 --> 00:04:09.699
Not only that, but you can also do modeling.

00:04:09.699 --> 00:04:17.179
And we have beyond like 50 feature transformers and modeling tools available in Spark.

00:04:17.179 --> 00:04:21.619
And you can access them from Sparkly R with ease.

00:04:21.619 --> 00:04:26.420
One of the features that we worked on last year was introducing pipelines, which Kevin

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:28.420
Kuo presented last year.

00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:36.299
And pipelines allow you to take those workflows that you have already completed on your modeling

00:04:36.299 --> 00:04:40.019
step and allows you to export them to production.

00:04:40.019 --> 00:04:41.220
What's new in Spark?

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:43.660
We covered streaming.

00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:47.220
Last year, we worked on MLib, which basically allows you to take a pipeline and export it

00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:52.899
out of Spark and put it into any Java-compatible environment that runs the JVM.

00:04:52.899 --> 00:04:58.260
We added support for Kubernetes and a little bit of RStudio 1.2 integration.

00:04:58.260 --> 00:05:04.019
So you have some of the great features of RStudio 1.2 are also available when using

00:05:04.019 --> 00:05:05.019
Spark.

00:05:05.019 --> 00:05:09.739
Like you can write a custom query, SQL query, or you can use the jobs pane just to track

00:05:09.739 --> 00:05:13.540
your Spark jobs and then reopen the job on Spark.

00:05:13.540 --> 00:05:14.660
What are we currently working on?

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:18.019
We're mainly working on two big features.

00:05:18.019 --> 00:05:23.019
One is support for Apache Arrow, and the other one is XGBoost on Spark.

00:05:23.019 --> 00:05:25.019
So what is Apache Arrow?

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:30.459
Wes did a much better job explaining this this morning.

00:05:30.459 --> 00:05:35.820
But the one-liner is Arrow is a cross-language platform for memory data.

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:39.260
Really the only thing that matters to you, I think in an ideal world, you don't even

00:05:39.260 --> 00:05:41.019
need to know what Arrow is.

00:05:41.019 --> 00:05:43.339
We just want to make things faster for you.

00:05:43.339 --> 00:05:46.179
And that's exactly what we're trying to accomplish.

00:05:46.179 --> 00:05:50.820
So you should be able to include the library, Arrow, and then SparklyR and get performance

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:51.820
improvements.

00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:54.500
Let's take a quick look to see how that looks like.

00:05:54.500 --> 00:05:55.500
Let's see.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:56.500
Where is this?

00:05:56.500 --> 00:05:57.500
Sorry about that.

00:05:57.500 --> 00:05:58.500
Yeah.

00:05:58.500 --> 00:06:11.820
So what we're going to do is we're going to start another Spark instance, so this is connecting

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:16.100
again locally, and then we're simply going to go and process 10,000 records.

00:06:16.100 --> 00:06:17.179
That's not that much.

00:06:17.179 --> 00:06:20.579
Usually the first time takes a little bit longer because Spark is warming up, but it's

00:06:20.579 --> 00:06:22.820
just 10,000 rows, which is not that much.

00:06:22.820 --> 00:06:28.179
This computer only has two cores and I think 8 gigabytes of RAM, so nothing fancy at all.

00:06:28.179 --> 00:06:33.299
So we're processing this data set, and it just takes nine seconds, and next time it

00:06:33.299 --> 00:06:36.540
should be a little bit faster.

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:40.220
But what is crazy is that once you run this with Arrow, which is not on CRAN yet, it's

00:06:40.220 --> 00:06:45.540
being underdeveloped, under active development, and once you run it with Arrow, we're processing

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:50.339
one million rows, so just not 10,000, a hundred times more data, and we're doing that on four

00:06:50.339 --> 00:06:51.339
seconds.

00:06:51.339 --> 00:06:56.019
So that is just, I don't even understand how this can be possible, but it's just great.

00:06:56.019 --> 00:07:00.059
So really hoping that you don't have to worry much about Arrow, but at least while using

00:07:00.059 --> 00:07:03.540
Sparkly you're going to get these performance improvements.

00:07:03.540 --> 00:07:08.500
And the other feature that we're working on is XGBoost on Spark, so you're going to be

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:13.140
able to train XGBoost models on Spark, and this is exactly what we're doing here.

00:07:13.140 --> 00:07:18.179
It's basically training, it's an extension that Kevin Koo is working on, and it trains

00:07:18.179 --> 00:07:21.100
basically a model using XGBoost.

00:07:21.100 --> 00:07:25.619
And what is great about this is that the next talk we're going to introduce MLflow, which

00:07:25.619 --> 00:07:29.779
is relevant to this case, because I'm basically leaving a model for Kevin to decide if he

00:07:29.779 --> 00:07:34.019
wants to use it on his talk, and he's going to teach you how to share models in a big

00:07:34.019 --> 00:07:35.019
data science team.

00:07:35.019 --> 00:07:37.779
Let me find back my presentation.

00:07:37.779 --> 00:07:41.420
All right, so we covered those two, and with that I just want to say thank you and leave

00:07:41.420 --> 00:07:42.500
you with some resources.

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:43.500
So thank you.

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:44.500
Awesome.

00:07:44.500 --> 00:07:52.579
Thank you so much, Javier.

